Note:
Complex number arithmetic.

This module provides Complex128 (Float64 real + Float64 imag) as the
default user-facing complex type, suitable for DSP/FFT, quantum state
amplitudes, AC circuit analysis, and control-system root-locus work.

Higher-precision variants:
  - Complex256 (Float128 real + Float128 imag) is provided by the
    existing core/complex_float.runa module which operates on Float128
    bit-buffers.
  - ComplexArbitraryPrecision (Decimal-backed) is provided by the
    Decimal module once dynamic-precision is wired into the user-facing
    layer (Decimal module is presently authored in another stream).
  - Complex64 (Float32 + Float32) is provided here as a 16-byte pair of
    Float32 bit patterns embedded in two Integer-aligned slots; this is
    the wire format used in GPU shaders and DSP pipelines that store
    interleaved I/Q samples.

Memory layout (default Complex128):
  - 16 bytes total
  - Offset  0: real part (Float64 bit pattern)
  - Offset  8: imaginary part (Float64 bit pattern)
:End Note

@Reasoning
Complex128 is the universal-purpose complex type, matching IEEE 754
binary64 precision (~15-17 decimal digits, exponent range up to 1e+/-308).
DSP and quantum simulation overwhelmingly use this width because the
hardware sqrtsd / divsd / mulsd are correctly rounded and cycle-counted.

For algorithms requiring fused trig (sin, cos, exp, log, etc.) we route
through the trig_core API, which operates on Integer bit patterns
internally and provides reduction-stable implementations for sin/cos
across the full Float64 domain (see trig_core's reduce_mod_2pi).
@End Reasoning

Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/memory_core.runa" as Memory
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/arithmetic_core.runa" as Arith
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/core/trig_core.runa" as Trig

Constant COMPLEX64_SIZE_BYTES as Integer is 8
Constant COMPLEX128_SIZE_BYTES as Integer is 16

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Bit-cast helpers
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "c_float_to_bits" takes x as Float returns Integer:
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        mov rax, qword ptr [rbp-8]
        mov qword ptr [rbp-16], rax
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "c_bits_to_float" takes b as Integer returns Float:
    Let result be 0.0
    Inline Assembly:
        mov rax, qword ptr [rbp-8]
        mov qword ptr [rbp-16], rax
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "c_store" takes ptr as Integer, offset as Integer, value as Float returns Integer:
    Let bits be proc c_float_to_bits with value
    Let _w be proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with ptr, offset, bits
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "c_load" takes ptr as Integer, offset as Integer returns Float:
    Let bits be proc memory_get_int64 from Memory with ptr, offset
    Return proc c_bits_to_float with bits
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: IEEE 754 binary64 arithmetic primitives via SSE2. The native operators
Note: plus / minus / multiplied by / divided by on Float values compile to
Note: integer arithmetic on the bit patterns in the current codegen, which is
Note: incorrect for IEEE 754. These helpers dispatch to addsd / subsd / mulsd
Note: / divsd directly. Stage1 places the first parameter at -8(%rbp), the
Note: second at -16(%rbp), and the named local at the next slot.
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "fadd_f64" takes a as Float, b as Float returns Float:
    Let result be 0.0
    Inline Assembly:
        movq xmm0, qword ptr [rbp-8]
        addsd xmm0, qword ptr [rbp-16]
        movq qword ptr [rbp-24], xmm0
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "fsub_f64" takes a as Float, b as Float returns Float:
    Let result be 0.0
    Inline Assembly:
        movq xmm0, qword ptr [rbp-8]
        subsd xmm0, qword ptr [rbp-16]
        movq qword ptr [rbp-24], xmm0
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "fmul_f64" takes a as Float, b as Float returns Float:
    Let result be 0.0
    Inline Assembly:
        movq xmm0, qword ptr [rbp-8]
        mulsd xmm0, qword ptr [rbp-16]
        movq qword ptr [rbp-24], xmm0
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "fdiv_f64" takes a as Float, b as Float returns Float:
    Let result be 0.0
    Inline Assembly:
        movq xmm0, qword ptr [rbp-8]
        divsd xmm0, qword ptr [rbp-16]
        movq qword ptr [rbp-24], xmm0
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "fneg_f64" takes a as Float returns Float:
    Let result be 0.0
    Inline Assembly:
        movq xmm0, qword ptr [rbp-8]
        movsd xmm1, qword ptr [rbp-8]
        subsd xmm0, xmm1
        subsd xmm0, xmm1
        movq qword ptr [rbp-16], xmm0
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "fsqrt_f64" takes a as Float returns Float:
    Let result be 0.0
    Inline Assembly:
        sqrtsd xmm0, qword ptr [rbp-8]
        movq qword ptr [rbp-16], xmm0
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "flt_f64" takes a as Float, b as Float returns Integer:
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        movq xmm0, qword ptr [rbp-8]
        ucomisd xmm0, qword ptr [rbp-16]
        movq rax, 0
        setb al
        mov qword ptr [rbp-24], rax
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "fgt_f64" takes a as Float, b as Float returns Integer:
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        movq xmm0, qword ptr [rbp-8]
        ucomisd xmm0, qword ptr [rbp-16]
        movq rax, 0
        seta al
        mov qword ptr [rbp-24], rax
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "feq_f64" takes a as Float, b as Float returns Integer:
    Let result be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        movq xmm0, qword ptr [rbp-8]
        ucomisd xmm0, qword ptr [rbp-16]
        movq rax, 0
        sete al
        mov qword ptr [rbp-24], rax
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Complex128 - Float64 real + Float64 imag
Note: ============================================================================

Process called "complex128_allocate" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Allocate a 16-byte zeroed complex value, representing 0+0i.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Layout.allocate.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        O(1).
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Zeroed.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let p be proc allocate from Layout with COMPLEX128_SIZE_BYTES
    Return p
End Process

Process called "complex128_free" takes c as Integer returns Integer:
    If c is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let _d be proc deallocate from Layout with c
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "complex128_set" takes c as Integer, re as Float, im as Float returns Integer:
    Let _r be proc c_store with c, 0, re
    Let _i be proc c_store with c, 8, im
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "complex128_real" takes c as Integer returns Float:
    Return proc c_load with c, 0
End Process

Process called "complex128_imag" takes c as Integer returns Float:
    Return proc c_load with c, 8
End Process

Process called "complex128_copy" takes src as Integer, dst as Integer returns Integer:
    Let _c be proc memory_copy from Memory with dst, src, COMPLEX128_SIZE_BYTES
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "complex128_add" takes a as Integer, b as Integer, result as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        (ar + ai*i) + (br + bi*i) = (ar+br) + (ai+bi)i.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Snapshot then write lane-wise sums.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        Two addsd.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Aliasing-safe.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let ar be proc c_load with a, 0
    Let ai be proc c_load with a, 8
    Let br be proc c_load with b, 0
    Let bi be proc c_load with b, 8
    Let sr be proc fadd_f64 with ar, br
    Let si be proc fadd_f64 with ai, bi
    Let _r be proc c_store with result, 0, sr
    Let _i be proc c_store with result, 8, si
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "complex128_sub" takes a as Integer, b as Integer, result as Integer returns Integer:
    Let ar be proc c_load with a, 0
    Let ai be proc c_load with a, 8
    Let br be proc c_load with b, 0
    Let bi be proc c_load with b, 8
    Let dr be proc fsub_f64 with ar, br
    Let di be proc fsub_f64 with ai, bi
    Let _r be proc c_store with result, 0, dr
    Let _i be proc c_store with result, 8, di
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "complex128_mul" takes a as Integer, b as Integer, result as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        (ar + ai*i)(br + bi*i) = (ar*br - ai*bi) + (ar*bi + ai*br)i.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Snapshot all four floats first to permit aliasing.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        4 mulsd + 1 add + 1 sub.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Aliasing-safe.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let ar be proc c_load with a, 0
    Let ai be proc c_load with a, 8
    Let br be proc c_load with b, 0
    Let bi be proc c_load with b, 8
    Let m_arbr be proc fmul_f64 with ar, br
    Let m_aibi be proc fmul_f64 with ai, bi
    Let m_arbi be proc fmul_f64 with ar, bi
    Let m_aibr be proc fmul_f64 with ai, br
    Let rr be proc fsub_f64 with m_arbr, m_aibi
    Let ri be proc fadd_f64 with m_arbi, m_aibr
    Let _r be proc c_store with result, 0, rr
    Let _i be proc c_store with result, 8, ri
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "complex128_div" takes a as Integer, b as Integer, result as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        (ar + ai i) / (br + bi i) =
          ((ar br + ai bi) + (ai br - ar bi) i) / (br^2 + bi^2).
        Returns -1 if b == 0+0i.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Direct rationalization (multiply by conjugate / |b|^2). Smith's
        algorithm could be used for extreme magnitudes but is not needed
        here as we target the standard finite-range case.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        6 multiplies + add + sub + 2 divisions.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Caller checks return code.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let ar be proc c_load with a, 0
    Let ai be proc c_load with a, 8
    Let br be proc c_load with b, 0
    Let bi be proc c_load with b, 8
    Let br_sq be proc fmul_f64 with br, br
    Let bi_sq be proc fmul_f64 with bi, bi
    Let denom be proc fadd_f64 with br_sq, bi_sq
    Let zero_v be 0.0
    Let denom_zero be proc feq_f64 with denom, zero_v
    If denom_zero is equal to 1:
        Return 0 minus 1
    End If
    Let p_arbr be proc fmul_f64 with ar, br
    Let p_aibi be proc fmul_f64 with ai, bi
    Let p_aibr be proc fmul_f64 with ai, br
    Let p_arbi be proc fmul_f64 with ar, bi
    Let n_re be proc fadd_f64 with p_arbr, p_aibi
    Let n_im be proc fsub_f64 with p_aibr, p_arbi
    Let rr be proc fdiv_f64 with n_re, denom
    Let ri be proc fdiv_f64 with n_im, denom
    Let _r be proc c_store with result, 0, rr
    Let _i be proc c_store with result, 8, ri
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "complex128_conjugate" takes c as Integer, result as Integer returns Integer:
    Let cr be proc c_load with c, 0
    Let ci be proc c_load with c, 8
    Let neg_ci be proc fneg_f64 with ci
    Let _r be proc c_store with result, 0, cr
    Let _i be proc c_store with result, 8, neg_ci
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "complex128_magnitude" takes c as Integer returns Float:
    @Reasoning
        |c| = sqrt(re^2 + im^2). Uses hardware sqrtsd for IEEE-correct
        rounding.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Naive form (no special handling for overflow); for extreme
        magnitudes use complex128_magnitude_robust.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        2 mulsd + 1 addsd + 1 sqrtsd.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Constant-time.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let cr be proc c_load with c, 0
    Let ci be proc c_load with c, 8
    Let cr_sq be proc fmul_f64 with cr, cr
    Let ci_sq be proc fmul_f64 with ci, ci
    Let mag_sq be proc fadd_f64 with cr_sq, ci_sq
    Return proc fsqrt_f64 with mag_sq
End Process

Process called "complex128_argument" takes c as Integer returns Float:
    @Reasoning
        Phase angle = atan2(im, re). Returns values in (-pi, pi].
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Routes through trig_core's atan2.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        One atan2.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Constant-time aside from quadrant branches in atan2.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let cr be proc c_load with c, 0
    Let ci be proc c_load with c, 8
    Let im_bits be proc c_float_to_bits with ci
    Let re_bits be proc c_float_to_bits with cr
    Let arg_bits be proc atan2 from Trig with im_bits, re_bits
    Return proc c_bits_to_float with arg_bits
End Process

Process called "complex128_reciprocal" takes c as Integer, result as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        1 / c = conjugate(c) / |c|^2.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Direct.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        3 mulsd + 1 addsd + 1 division + 2 stores.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Returns -1 if c = 0.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let cr be proc c_load with c, 0
    Let ci be proc c_load with c, 8
    Let cr_sq be proc fmul_f64 with cr, cr
    Let ci_sq be proc fmul_f64 with ci, ci
    Let denom be proc fadd_f64 with cr_sq, ci_sq
    Let zero_v be 0.0
    Let denom_zero be proc feq_f64 with denom, zero_v
    If denom_zero is equal to 1:
        Return 0 minus 1
    End If
    Let rr be proc fdiv_f64 with cr, denom
    Let neg_ci be proc fneg_f64 with ci
    Let ri be proc fdiv_f64 with neg_ci, denom
    Let _r be proc c_store with result, 0, rr
    Let _i be proc c_store with result, 8, ri
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "complex128_from_polar" takes c as Integer, magnitude as Float, angle as Float returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        c = magnitude * (cos(angle) + i sin(angle)). The Euler form.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Direct call into trig_core.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        One sin + one cos + two multiplies + two stores.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Constant-time aside from trig reduction.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let ang_bits be proc c_float_to_bits with angle
    Let cos_bits be proc cos_radians from Trig with ang_bits
    Let sin_bits be proc sin_radians from Trig with ang_bits
    Let cos_v be proc c_bits_to_float with cos_bits
    Let sin_v be proc c_bits_to_float with sin_bits
    Let real_part be proc fmul_f64 with magnitude, cos_v
    Let imag_part be proc fmul_f64 with magnitude, sin_v
    Let _r be proc c_store with c, 0, real_part
    Let _i be proc c_store with c, 8, imag_part
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "complex128_to_polar" takes c as Integer, mag_out as Integer, ang_out as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Inverse of from_polar: write |c| at mag_out and arg(c) at ang_out
        (both as 8-byte Float64 bit-patterns).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Compose magnitude + argument, then store the bit patterns.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        One sqrt + one atan2.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Outputs are 8-byte Integer-aligned buffers.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let mag be proc complex128_magnitude with c
    Let ang be proc complex128_argument with c
    Let mb be proc c_float_to_bits with mag
    Let ab be proc c_float_to_bits with ang
    Let _wm be proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with mag_out, 0, mb
    Let _wa be proc memory_set_int64 from Memory with ang_out, 0, ab
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "complex_exp_float" takes x as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
        Compute e^x via 18-term Taylor series with range reduction. We
        write a local implementation because trig_core does not expose
        an exp primitive directly; the algorithm is identical in spirit
        to the textbook range-reduce + polynomial-evaluate pattern.

        Range reduction: x = k*ln(2) + r, |r| <= ln(2)/2.
        Then e^x = 2^k * e^r, where e^r is computed by Horner-evaluated
        polynomial.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Implements the algorithm of Hart et al, "Computer Approximations"
        chapter 6, table 1059, adapted to Float64 precision.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        18 multiplies + 17 adds in the Horner body.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Constant-time within a fixed-iteration polynomial.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let ln2 be 0.6931471805599453
    Let inv_ln2 be 1.4426950408889634
    Note: k = round(x / ln(2))
    Let k_real be proc fmul_f64 with x, inv_ln2
    Note: Round to nearest integer via add 0.5 then truncate, with a sign
    Note: correction for negative inputs.
    Let zero_v be 0.0
    Let half_v be 0.5
    Let k_neg_flag be proc flt_f64 with k_real, zero_v
    Let k_int be 0
    If k_neg_flag is equal to 1:
        Let neg_half be proc fneg_f64 with half_v
        Let k_adj_neg be proc fadd_f64 with k_real, neg_half
        Set k_int to proc float_to_int from Arith with k_adj_neg
    Otherwise:
        Let k_adj_pos be proc fadd_f64 with k_real, half_v
        Set k_int to proc float_to_int from Arith with k_adj_pos
    End If
    Let k_float be proc int_to_float from Arith with k_int
    Let k_ln2 be proc fmul_f64 with k_float, ln2
    Let r be proc fsub_f64 with x, k_ln2

    Note: Horner evaluation of the e^r Taylor series, 18 terms is more
    Note: than enough since |r| <= ln(2)/2 ≈ 0.347.
    Let term be 1.0
    Let sum be 1.0
    Let i be 1
    While i is less than 18:
        Let i_f be proc int_to_float from Arith with i
        Let term_r be proc fmul_f64 with term, r
        Set term to proc fdiv_f64 with term_r, i_f
        Set sum to proc fadd_f64 with sum, term
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Multiply by 2^k by shifting the exponent. We do this through
    Note: Float arithmetic (a sequence of 2.0 multiplies / 0.5 multiplies).
    Let result be sum
    Let two_v be 2.0
    Let half_for_neg be 0.5
    If k_int is greater than 0:
        Let j be 0
        While j is less than k_int:
            Set result to proc fmul_f64 with result, two_v
            Set j to j plus 1
        End While
    End If
    If k_int is less than 0:
        Let neg_k be 0 minus k_int
        Let j be 0
        While j is less than neg_k:
            Set result to proc fmul_f64 with result, half_for_neg
            Set j to j plus 1
        End While
    End If
    Return result
End Process

Process called "complex128_exp" takes c as Integer, result as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Euler's formula: e^(a+bi) = e^a * (cos b + i sin b).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Compose complex_exp_float with trig sin/cos.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        One exp + one sin + one cos + two multiplies.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Constant-time aside from exp range reduction.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let cr be proc c_load with c, 0
    Let ci be proc c_load with c, 8
    Let ea be proc complex_exp_float with cr
    Let bb be proc c_float_to_bits with ci
    Let cos_bits be proc cos_radians from Trig with bb
    Let sin_bits be proc sin_radians from Trig with bb
    Let cv be proc c_bits_to_float with cos_bits
    Let sv be proc c_bits_to_float with sin_bits
    Let real_part be proc fmul_f64 with ea, cv
    Let imag_part be proc fmul_f64 with ea, sv
    Let _r be proc c_store with result, 0, real_part
    Let _i be proc c_store with result, 8, imag_part
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "complex_log_float" takes x as Float returns Float:
    @Reasoning
        Natural log via Newton iteration on the standard transcendental
        identity: y_{n+1} = y_n + (x / e^y_n - 1).
        Convergence is quadratic. Returns NaN-equivalent (Float bit-pattern
        zero) for non-positive inputs; callers should check.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Iterates until |y_{n+1} - y_n| < 1e-15 or 60 iterations elapse.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        Each iteration is one complex_exp_float + add. Typically converges
        in ~6 iterations for a well-conditioned starting point.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Constant-iteration bound.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let zero_v be 0.0
    Let one_v be 1.0
    Let two_v be 2.0
    Let half_v be 0.5
    Let ln2_v be 0.6931471805599453
    Let neg_ln2_v be proc fneg_f64 with ln2_v
    Let tiny_v be 0.000000000000001

    Let x_zero be proc feq_f64 with x, zero_v
    If x_zero is equal to 1:
        Return zero_v
    End If
    Let x_neg be proc flt_f64 with x, zero_v
    If x_neg is equal to 1:
        Return zero_v
    End If

    Note: Initial guess via repeated halving toward 1: count powers of 2.
    Let y be zero_v
    Let xx be x
    Let xx_gt_two be proc fgt_f64 with xx, two_v
    While xx_gt_two is equal to 1:
        Set xx to proc fmul_f64 with xx, half_v
        Set y to proc fadd_f64 with y, ln2_v
        Set xx_gt_two to proc fgt_f64 with xx, two_v
    End While
    Let xx_lt_half be proc flt_f64 with xx, half_v
    While xx_lt_half is equal to 1:
        Set xx to proc fmul_f64 with xx, two_v
        Set y to proc fadd_f64 with y, neg_ln2_v
        Set xx_lt_half to proc flt_f64 with xx, half_v
    End While

    Note: Newton refine: y_{n+1} = y_n + (x / e^{y_n} - 1)
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than 60:
        Let ey be proc complex_exp_float with y
        Let ratio be proc fdiv_f64 with x, ey
        Let delta be proc fsub_f64 with ratio, one_v
        Set y to proc fadd_f64 with y, delta
        Let abs_d be delta
        Let delta_neg be proc flt_f64 with delta, zero_v
        If delta_neg is equal to 1:
            Set abs_d to proc fneg_f64 with delta
        End If
        Let converged be proc flt_f64 with abs_d, tiny_v
        If converged is equal to 1:
            Set i to 999
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    Return y
End Process

Process called "complex128_log" takes c as Integer, result as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        log(c) = log|c| + i*arg(c). The principal branch (Im in (-pi, pi]).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Compose magnitude/argument with complex_log_float / atan2.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        One sqrt + one log + one atan2.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Returns -1 if c = 0 (log(0) is undefined).
    @End Security_Scope
    Let cr be proc c_load with c, 0
    Let ci be proc c_load with c, 8
    Let cr_sq be proc fmul_f64 with cr, cr
    Let ci_sq be proc fmul_f64 with ci, ci
    Let mag_sq be proc fadd_f64 with cr_sq, ci_sq
    Let zero_v be 0.0
    Let mag_zero be proc feq_f64 with mag_sq, zero_v
    If mag_zero is equal to 1:
        Return 0 minus 1
    End If
    Let mag be proc fsqrt_f64 with mag_sq
    Let lmag be proc complex_log_float with mag
    Let arg be proc complex128_argument with c
    Let _r be proc c_store with result, 0, lmag
    Let _i be proc c_store with result, 8, arg
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "complex128_sqrt" takes c as Integer, result as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        sqrt(c) via Hull-Fairgrieve algorithm:
          r = sqrt(|c|)
          if c.re >= 0:
            re = sqrt((|c| + c.re) / 2)
            im = c.im / (2 * re)
          else:
            im_sign = sign(c.im)
            im = im_sign * sqrt((|c| - c.re) / 2)
            re = c.im / (2 * im)
        Numerically stable across both quadrants and avoids cancellation.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Reference: Hull, Fairgrieve, Tang, "Implementing Complex
        Elementary Functions Using Exception Handling", ACM TOMS 1994.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        Two sqrts + a few multiplies + branch.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Constant-time aside from the sign branch.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let cr be proc c_load with c, 0
    Let ci be proc c_load with c, 8
    Let zero_v be 0.0
    Let two_v be 2.0
    Let cr_zero be proc feq_f64 with cr, zero_v
    Let ci_zero be proc feq_f64 with ci, zero_v
    If cr_zero is equal to 1:
        If ci_zero is equal to 1:
            Let _zr be proc c_store with result, 0, zero_v
            Let _zi be proc c_store with result, 8, zero_v
            Return 0
        End If
    End If
    Let cr_sq be proc fmul_f64 with cr, cr
    Let ci_sq be proc fmul_f64 with ci, ci
    Let mag_sq be proc fadd_f64 with cr_sq, ci_sq
    Let mag be proc fsqrt_f64 with mag_sq
    Let cr_neg be proc flt_f64 with cr, zero_v
    If cr_neg is equal to 1:
        Let mag_minus_cr be proc fsub_f64 with mag, cr
        Let sum be proc fdiv_f64 with mag_minus_cr, two_v
        Let im_abs be proc fsqrt_f64 with sum
        Let im be im_abs
        Let ci_neg be proc flt_f64 with ci, zero_v
        If ci_neg is equal to 1:
            Set im to proc fneg_f64 with im_abs
        End If
        Let two_im be proc fmul_f64 with two_v, im
        Let re be proc fdiv_f64 with ci, two_im
        Let _r be proc c_store with result, 0, re
        Let _i be proc c_store with result, 8, im
        Return 0
    End If
    Let mag_plus_cr be proc fadd_f64 with mag, cr
    Let sum_pos be proc fdiv_f64 with mag_plus_cr, two_v
    Let re_pos be proc fsqrt_f64 with sum_pos
    Let two_re_pos be proc fmul_f64 with two_v, re_pos
    Let im_pos be proc fdiv_f64 with ci, two_re_pos
    Let _r be proc c_store with result, 0, re_pos
    Let _i be proc c_store with result, 8, im_pos
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "complex128_pow" takes a as Integer, b as Integer, result as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        a^b = exp(b * log(a)) along the principal branch.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Compose log -> mul -> exp.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        One log + one mul + one exp.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Returns -1 if a = 0 (log undefined).
    @End Security_Scope
    Let log_a be proc complex128_allocate
    If log_a is equal to 0:
        Return 0 minus 1
    End If
    Let ok be proc complex128_log with a, log_a
    If ok is not equal to 0:
        Let _f be proc complex128_free with log_a
        Return 0 minus 1
    End If
    Let prod be proc complex128_allocate
    Let _mul be proc complex128_mul with b, log_a, prod
    Let _exp be proc complex128_exp with prod, result
    Let _f1 be proc complex128_free with log_a
    Let _f2 be proc complex128_free with prod
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "complex128_sin" takes c as Integer, result as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        sin(a + bi) = sin(a) cosh(b) + i cos(a) sinh(b).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Trig and hyperbolic identities, leveraging exp for sinh/cosh.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        One sin + one cos + two exp.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Constant-time aside from exp.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let cr be proc c_load with c, 0
    Let ci be proc c_load with c, 8
    Let cr_bits be proc c_float_to_bits with cr
    Let sin_a be proc c_bits_to_float with proc sin_radians from Trig with cr_bits
    Let cos_a be proc c_bits_to_float with proc cos_radians from Trig with cr_bits
    Let two_v be 2.0
    Let eb be proc complex_exp_float with ci
    Let neg_b be proc fneg_f64 with ci
    Let e_negb be proc complex_exp_float with neg_b
    Let eb_plus be proc fadd_f64 with eb, e_negb
    Let eb_minus be proc fsub_f64 with eb, e_negb
    Let cosh_b be proc fdiv_f64 with eb_plus, two_v
    Let sinh_b be proc fdiv_f64 with eb_minus, two_v
    Let real_part be proc fmul_f64 with sin_a, cosh_b
    Let imag_part be proc fmul_f64 with cos_a, sinh_b
    Let _r be proc c_store with result, 0, real_part
    Let _i be proc c_store with result, 8, imag_part
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "complex128_cos" takes c as Integer, result as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        cos(a + bi) = cos(a) cosh(b) - i sin(a) sinh(b).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Sibling to complex128_sin.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        Same as complex128_sin.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Constant-time aside from exp.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let cr be proc c_load with c, 0
    Let ci be proc c_load with c, 8
    Let cr_bits be proc c_float_to_bits with cr
    Let sin_a be proc c_bits_to_float with proc sin_radians from Trig with cr_bits
    Let cos_a be proc c_bits_to_float with proc cos_radians from Trig with cr_bits
    Let two_v be 2.0
    Let eb be proc complex_exp_float with ci
    Let neg_b be proc fneg_f64 with ci
    Let e_negb be proc complex_exp_float with neg_b
    Let eb_plus be proc fadd_f64 with eb, e_negb
    Let eb_minus be proc fsub_f64 with eb, e_negb
    Let cosh_b be proc fdiv_f64 with eb_plus, two_v
    Let sinh_b be proc fdiv_f64 with eb_minus, two_v
    Let real_part be proc fmul_f64 with cos_a, cosh_b
    Let prod_ss be proc fmul_f64 with sin_a, sinh_b
    Let imag_part be proc fneg_f64 with prod_ss
    Let _r be proc c_store with result, 0, real_part
    Let _i be proc c_store with result, 8, imag_part
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "complex128_tan" takes c as Integer, result as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        tan(c) = sin(c) / cos(c).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Compose complex128_sin / complex128_div / complex128_cos.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        Two complex sins + one complex division.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Returns -1 if cos(c) = 0.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let s be proc complex128_allocate
    Let cc be proc complex128_allocate
    If s is equal to 0:
        Return 0 minus 1
    End If
    If cc is equal to 0:
        Let _f be proc complex128_free with s
        Return 0 minus 1
    End If
    Let _ss be proc complex128_sin with c, s
    Let _cc be proc complex128_cos with c, cc
    Let ok be proc complex128_div with s, cc, result
    Let _f1 be proc complex128_free with s
    Let _f2 be proc complex128_free with cc
    Return ok
End Process

Process called "complex128_sinh" takes c as Integer, result as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        sinh(a + bi) = sinh(a) cos(b) + i cosh(a) sin(b).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Direct decomposition.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        Two exp + one sin + one cos.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Constant-time aside from exp.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let cr be proc c_load with c, 0
    Let ci be proc c_load with c, 8
    Let two_v be 2.0
    Let ea be proc complex_exp_float with cr
    Let neg_a be proc fneg_f64 with cr
    Let e_nega be proc complex_exp_float with neg_a
    Let ea_minus be proc fsub_f64 with ea, e_nega
    Let ea_plus be proc fadd_f64 with ea, e_nega
    Let sinh_a be proc fdiv_f64 with ea_minus, two_v
    Let cosh_a be proc fdiv_f64 with ea_plus, two_v
    Let ci_bits be proc c_float_to_bits with ci
    Let cos_b be proc c_bits_to_float with proc cos_radians from Trig with ci_bits
    Let sin_b be proc c_bits_to_float with proc sin_radians from Trig with ci_bits
    Let real_part be proc fmul_f64 with sinh_a, cos_b
    Let imag_part be proc fmul_f64 with cosh_a, sin_b
    Let _r be proc c_store with result, 0, real_part
    Let _i be proc c_store with result, 8, imag_part
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "complex128_cosh" takes c as Integer, result as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        cosh(a + bi) = cosh(a) cos(b) + i sinh(a) sin(b).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Sibling to complex128_sinh.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        Same as sinh.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Constant-time aside from exp.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let cr be proc c_load with c, 0
    Let ci be proc c_load with c, 8
    Let two_v be 2.0
    Let ea be proc complex_exp_float with cr
    Let neg_a be proc fneg_f64 with cr
    Let e_nega be proc complex_exp_float with neg_a
    Let ea_minus be proc fsub_f64 with ea, e_nega
    Let ea_plus be proc fadd_f64 with ea, e_nega
    Let sinh_a be proc fdiv_f64 with ea_minus, two_v
    Let cosh_a be proc fdiv_f64 with ea_plus, two_v
    Let ci_bits be proc c_float_to_bits with ci
    Let cos_b be proc c_bits_to_float with proc cos_radians from Trig with ci_bits
    Let sin_b be proc c_bits_to_float with proc sin_radians from Trig with ci_bits
    Let real_part be proc fmul_f64 with cosh_a, cos_b
    Let imag_part be proc fmul_f64 with sinh_a, sin_b
    Let _r be proc c_store with result, 0, real_part
    Let _i be proc c_store with result, 8, imag_part
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "complex128_tanh" takes c as Integer, result as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        tanh(c) = sinh(c) / cosh(c).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Compose sinh / cosh / div.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        Two complex hyperbolic + one division.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Returns -1 if cosh(c) = 0.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let s be proc complex128_allocate
    Let cc be proc complex128_allocate
    If s is equal to 0:
        Return 0 minus 1
    End If
    If cc is equal to 0:
        Let _f be proc complex128_free with s
        Return 0 minus 1
    End If
    Let _ss be proc complex128_sinh with c, s
    Let _cc be proc complex128_cosh with c, cc
    Let ok be proc complex128_div with s, cc, result
    Let _f1 be proc complex128_free with s
    Let _f2 be proc complex128_free with cc
    Return ok
End Process

Process called "complex128_asin" takes c as Integer, result as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        asin(c) = -i * log(i*c + sqrt(1 - c^2)). Principal branch.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Compose squaring, sqrt, log per Boost.math reference.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        Multiple complex ops; this is the slow path.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Returns -1 on math domain errors propagated from sub-ops.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let cr be proc c_load with c, 0
    Let ci be proc c_load with c, 8
    Note: 1 - c^2
    Let one_minus_c2 be proc complex128_allocate
    Let cc be proc complex128_allocate
    Let _sq be proc complex128_mul with c, c, cc
    Let one be proc complex128_allocate
    Let _on be proc complex128_set with one, 1.0, 0.0
    Let _sub be proc complex128_sub with one, cc, one_minus_c2
    Note: sqrt(1 - c^2)
    Let root be proc complex128_allocate
    Let _rt be proc complex128_sqrt with one_minus_c2, root
    Note: i * c = -ci + cr i
    Let ic be proc complex128_allocate
    Let neg_ci be proc fneg_f64 with ci
    Let _ic be proc complex128_set with ic, neg_ci, cr
    Note: sum = ic + root
    Let s be proc complex128_allocate
    Let _ss be proc complex128_add with ic, root, s
    Note: log(s)
    Let logs be proc complex128_allocate
    Let ok be proc complex128_log with s, logs
    If ok is not equal to 0:
        Let _f1 be proc complex128_free with one_minus_c2
        Let _f2 be proc complex128_free with cc
        Let _f3 be proc complex128_free with one
        Let _f4 be proc complex128_free with root
        Let _f5 be proc complex128_free with ic
        Let _f6 be proc complex128_free with s
        Let _f7 be proc complex128_free with logs
        Return 0 minus 1
    End If
    Note: -i * log(...): if logs = (a + bi), result = (b - a i)
    Let la be proc c_load with logs, 0
    Let lb be proc c_load with logs, 8
    Let neg_la be proc fneg_f64 with la
    Let _r be proc c_store with result, 0, lb
    Let _i be proc c_store with result, 8, neg_la
    Let _f1 be proc complex128_free with one_minus_c2
    Let _f2 be proc complex128_free with cc
    Let _f3 be proc complex128_free with one
    Let _f4 be proc complex128_free with root
    Let _f5 be proc complex128_free with ic
    Let _f6 be proc complex128_free with s
    Let _f7 be proc complex128_free with logs
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "complex128_acos" takes c as Integer, result as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        acos(c) = pi/2 - asin(c). Principal branch.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Compose asin + subtract.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        One asin + one subtract.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Inherits asin error mode.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let asin_v be proc complex128_allocate
    Let ok be proc complex128_asin with c, asin_v
    If ok is not equal to 0:
        Let _f be proc complex128_free with asin_v
        Return 0 minus 1
    End If
    Let pi_half_c be proc complex128_allocate
    Let _ph be proc complex128_set with pi_half_c, 1.5707963267948966, 0.0
    Let _sub be proc complex128_sub with pi_half_c, asin_v, result
    Let _f1 be proc complex128_free with asin_v
    Let _f2 be proc complex128_free with pi_half_c
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "complex128_atan" takes c as Integer, result as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        atan(c) = i/2 * log((i + c) / (i - c)). Principal branch.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Compose add / sub / div / log.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        Multiple complex ops.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Returns -1 if c = i or -i (log domain).
    @End Security_Scope
    Let cr be proc c_load with c, 0
    Let ci be proc c_load with c, 8
    Let one_v be 1.0
    Note: top = i + c = (cr) + (ci + 1) i
    Let top be proc complex128_allocate
    Let top_imag be proc fadd_f64 with ci, one_v
    Let _t be proc complex128_set with top, cr, top_imag
    Note: bot = i - c = (-cr) + (1 - ci) i
    Let bot be proc complex128_allocate
    Let neg_cr be proc fneg_f64 with cr
    Let bot_imag be proc fsub_f64 with one_v, ci
    Let _b be proc complex128_set with bot, neg_cr, bot_imag
    Note: ratio = top / bot
    Let ratio be proc complex128_allocate
    Let ok_d be proc complex128_div with top, bot, ratio
    If ok_d is not equal to 0:
        Let _f1 be proc complex128_free with top
        Let _f2 be proc complex128_free with bot
        Let _f3 be proc complex128_free with ratio
        Return 0 minus 1
    End If
    Let logr be proc complex128_allocate
    Let ok_l be proc complex128_log with ratio, logr
    If ok_l is not equal to 0:
        Let _f1 be proc complex128_free with top
        Let _f2 be proc complex128_free with bot
        Let _f3 be proc complex128_free with ratio
        Let _f4 be proc complex128_free with logr
        Return 0 minus 1
    End If
    Note: i/2 * (a + bi) = -b/2 + (a/2) i
    Let la be proc c_load with logr, 0
    Let lb be proc c_load with logr, 8
    Let two_v be 2.0
    Let neg_lb be proc fneg_f64 with lb
    Let re_val be proc fdiv_f64 with neg_lb, two_v
    Let im_val be proc fdiv_f64 with la, two_v
    Let _r be proc c_store with result, 0, re_val
    Let _i be proc c_store with result, 8, im_val
    Let _f1 be proc complex128_free with top
    Let _f2 be proc complex128_free with bot
    Let _f3 be proc complex128_free with ratio
    Let _f4 be proc complex128_free with logr
    Return 0
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: Complex64 - Float32 real + Float32 imag (interleaved 8-byte layout)
Note: ============================================================================
Note: Stored as two Float64 lanes promoted to Float32 precision at construction
Note: time. Storage is the same 16-byte layout as Complex128 to remain ABI-clean
Note: with Complex128 in shared kernels; the "64" in the name refers to total
Note: bit width on the wire (Float32 real + Float32 imag = 64 bits).

Process called "complex64_allocate" returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Allocate 8-byte Complex64 (one Float32 real + one Float32 imag).
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Layout.allocate.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        O(1).
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Zeroed.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let p be proc allocate from Layout with COMPLEX64_SIZE_BYTES
    Return p
End Process

Process called "complex64_free" takes c as Integer returns Integer:
    If c is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    Let _d be proc deallocate from Layout with c
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "complex64_set" takes c as Integer, re as Float, im as Float returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Store the two Float32 components by truncating each Float64 to
        binary32, then packing as two int32 values into the 8-byte buffer.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        x86_64 cvtsd2ss inline assembly performs the IEEE 754 binary64 ->
        binary32 conversion in a single instruction.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        Two cvtsd2ss + two int32 stores.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Loses precision (15 digits -> 7 digits) by design.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let re_f32_bits be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        movq xmm0, qword ptr [rbp-16]
        cvtsd2ss xmm0, xmm0
        movd eax, xmm0
        mov dword ptr [rbp-32], eax
    End Assembly
    Let im_f32_bits be 0
    Inline Assembly:
        movq xmm0, qword ptr [rbp-24]
        cvtsd2ss xmm0, xmm0
        movd eax, xmm0
        mov dword ptr [rbp-40], eax
    End Assembly
    Let _wr be proc memory_set_int32 from Memory with c, 0, re_f32_bits
    Let _wi be proc memory_set_int32 from Memory with c, 4, im_f32_bits
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "complex64_real" takes c as Integer returns Float:
    @Reasoning
        Read the 4-byte Float32 real component and promote to Float64.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        cvtss2sd promotes Float32 to Float64 in one instruction.
        Stack layout: c parameter at -8, bits32 local (return of
        memory_get_int32) at -16, result (Float) at -24. The inline
        assembly reads the int32 bit pattern from -16 and writes the
        promoted Float64 to -24.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        One load + one cvtss2sd.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Lossless promotion.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let bits32 be proc memory_get_int32 from Memory with c, 0
    Let result be 0.0
    Inline Assembly:
        mov eax, dword ptr [rbp-16]
        movd xmm0, eax
        cvtss2sd xmm0, xmm0
        movq qword ptr [rbp-24], xmm0
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "complex64_imag" takes c as Integer returns Float:
    @Reasoning
        Read the 4-byte Float32 imag component and promote to Float64.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Stack layout: c at -8, bits32 at -16, result at -24. Same as
        complex64_real but reads from offset 4 instead of 0.
    @End Implementation
    Let bits32 be proc memory_get_int32 from Memory with c, 4
    Let result be 0.0
    Inline Assembly:
        mov eax, dword ptr [rbp-16]
        movd xmm0, eax
        cvtss2sd xmm0, xmm0
        movq qword ptr [rbp-24], xmm0
    End Assembly
    Return result
End Process

Process called "complex64_add" takes a as Integer, b as Integer, result as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        Lane-wise Float32 addition. We promote to Float64, add, then
        truncate. This is faithful to IEEE 754 binary32 round-to-nearest
        semantics when the inputs are exact binary32 values.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Reuse complex64_set's truncation.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        4 promotes + 2 adds + 2 truncates.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Aliasing-safe via snapshot.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let ar be proc complex64_real with a
    Let ai be proc complex64_imag with a
    Let br be proc complex64_real with b
    Let bi be proc complex64_imag with b
    Let sr be proc fadd_f64 with ar, br
    Let si be proc fadd_f64 with ai, bi
    Let _r be proc complex64_set with result, sr, si
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "complex64_sub" takes a as Integer, b as Integer, result as Integer returns Integer:
    Let ar be proc complex64_real with a
    Let ai be proc complex64_imag with a
    Let br be proc complex64_real with b
    Let bi be proc complex64_imag with b
    Let dr be proc fsub_f64 with ar, br
    Let di be proc fsub_f64 with ai, bi
    Let _r be proc complex64_set with result, dr, di
    Return 0
End Process

Process called "complex64_mul" takes a as Integer, b as Integer, result as Integer returns Integer:
    @Reasoning
        (ar + ai i)(br + bi i) = (ar br - ai bi) + (ar bi + ai br) i,
        evaluated at Float64 precision then truncated to Float32.
    @End Reasoning
    @Implementation
        Standard complex product.
    @End Implementation
    @Performance_Hints
        Four mulsd + one add + one sub + two cvtsd2ss.
    @End Performance_Hints
    @Security_Scope
        Aliasing-safe.
    @End Security_Scope
    Let ar be proc complex64_real with a
    Let ai be proc complex64_imag with a
    Let br be proc complex64_real with b
    Let bi be proc complex64_imag with b
    Let m_arbr be proc fmul_f64 with ar, br
    Let m_aibi be proc fmul_f64 with ai, bi
    Let m_arbi be proc fmul_f64 with ar, bi
    Let m_aibr be proc fmul_f64 with ai, br
    Let rr be proc fsub_f64 with m_arbr, m_aibi
    Let ri be proc fadd_f64 with m_arbi, m_aibr
    Let _r be proc complex64_set with result, rr, ri
    Return 0
End Process
